      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>33.</num>
        <content>
          <p>The Work Life Balance Survey did not examine the duration for which unpaid carer’s leave was taken. However, it is reasonable to expect that not all carers will use the full 5 days of Carer’s Leave available to them. Some carers will find fewer days sufficient for them to fulfil their caring needs, i.e., supporting someone who is attending a single hospital appointment. In addition to this, as this is an unpaid leave entitlement some carers will be disincentivised to take the full entitlement of leave, as they do not want to lose more of their income. Existing survey evidence shows that one of the key reasons for not taking leave is because of affordability.<authorialNote marker="38"><p> Maternity and Paternity Rights Survey (2009/10) </p></authorialNote> Therefore, it makes sense to taper the take-up rate, so it is highest for day 1 and lowest for day 5. We have modelled this with a simple linear taper and increased/decreased the take-up rate by 1.5% for the central scenario (0.5% for the low scenario and 3% for the high scenario) around the mean on day 3. This approach has been endorsed as a reasonable assumption to make the absence of stronger evidence by relevant stakeholders - Carer’s UK and CIPD.  </p>
        </content>
